# Why Is Illegal Immigration a Controversial Issue?  
_A Detailed Analytical Report_

---

## Introduction

Illegal immigration remains one of the most contentious and polarizing issues in contemporary political, social, and economic discourse, particularly in countries like the United States. The controversy stems from multifaceted impacts spanning economic, social, cultural, and political domains. This report aims to provide a comprehensive, well-structured, and evidence-based analysis of why illegal immigration is controversial, drawing from a wide range of scholarly articles, government data, and expert analyses. It will also offer a critical opinion based on the reviewed information.

---

## 1. Economic Factors

### 1.1 Labor Market Effects

Illegal immigrants often occupy low-wage, low-skilled jobs that many native-born workers avoid, such as agricultural labor, construction, and service industries. While this labor supply can benefit employers by reducing costs, it also creates downward pressure on wages and employment opportunities for low-skilled native workers. Studies suggest that illegal immigration has contributed to wage declines and job displacement among certain segments of the native workforce, particularly high school dropouts and low-skilled workers ([UKEssays, 2015](https://www.ukessays.com/essays/politics/thesis-statement-on-illegal-immigrants-politics-essay.php?vref=1)).

A Harvard study found that immigration lowered wages of high school dropouts by nearly 8% between 1980 and 2000. Additionally, an estimated 1.88 million American workers are displaced annually due to immigrant competition, costing over $15 billion in welfare and assistance ([FAIR, 2004](https://www.fairus.org/issue/illegal-immigration)).

### 1.2 Fiscal Impact and Public Services

Illegal immigrants contribute to the economy through labor and taxes but often use public services disproportionately relative to their tax contributions. The National Research Council (1997) estimated that immigrants without a high school education impose a net fiscal burden of $89,000 over their lifetime, while those with only a high school education impose a $31,000 burden.

The Center for Immigration Studies (2004) estimated that illegal immigrant households used $10 billion more in government services than they paid in taxes in 2002, including Medicaid, food assistance, and education. Public schools face significant costs educating children of illegal immigrants, with an estimated $7.4 billion annually spent on K-12 education for illegal immigrant children ([FAIR, 2004](https://www.fairus.org/issue/illegal-immigration)).

### 1.3 Remittances and Wealth Transfer

Illegal immigrants send substantial remittances to their home countries, amounting to $30 billion annually, with Mexico receiving $13.3 billion. This transfer of wealth represents a significant outflow from the U.S. economy and is a source of concern for those who see it as subsidizing foreign economies at the expense of American taxpayers ([FAIR, 2004](https://www.fairus.org/issue/illegal-immigration)).

